  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT223-kilavi">varaiviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa kiḻattiyatu vēṟupāṭu kaṇṭu vaṟpuṟuttun tōḻikkuk kiḻatti <app><lem>uraittatu</lem><rdg wit="#G2">kūṟiyatu</rdg></app>
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante who encourages [her] at
          the sight of changes in HER, who had changed [while awaiting] the time of marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT223">
          <l>pērūr koṇṭa vārkali viḻaviṟ<app><note xml:lang="en">line 1 missing in #L1.</note></app></l>
          <l>celvāñ celvā meṉṟi yaṉṟiva</l>
          <l>ṇallōr nalla palavāṟ ṟilla</l>
          <l>taḻalun taṭṭaiyu muṟiyun tantivai</l>
          <l>yottaṉa niṉakkeṉap poyttaṉa kūṟi</l>
          <l>yaṉṉai yōmpiya vāynala</l>
          <l>meṉṉai koṇṭāṉyā miṉṉamā liṉiyē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">

          <l>On that day you <note place="foot">Here syntax is tricky, and the addressee of the
            first lines is not marked at all. Perhaps we can work with a switch of perspective,
            namely at first HER remembering the man's words, then an account of what happened
            further. T.V.G. takes the beginning as HER report of the confidante's words, who induces
            her to go to the festival once again, while afterwards she relates what happened the
            last time they went there.</note> would say: “let us go</l>
          <l rend="indent2">to the bustling festival in the big village!” There</l>
          <l>[were] many good things for the good ones indeed <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">-āl-tilla</term> without -ē seems to be longingly-surprised
            affirmation.</note> ! <note place="foot">This sentence can be read as HER commentary on
            the festival scene, or a second part of the quoted direct speech, that his, HIS argument
            for going to the festival. T.V.G., however, explains it as the good omens that speak in
            favour of going to the festival.</note>
          </l>
          <l>He gave [me] a Taḻal and a Taṭṭai and a shoot</l>
          <l>[and] spoke <note place="foot">It is also possible to read the two absolutives <term xml:lang="ta">tantu</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">kūṟi</term> as dependent on <term xml:lang="ta">aṉṉai</term> , as L./Sh.P. do (= 4-7c). But how to arrive from there
            at the notion of guarding the fields is mysterious. A better point is made if HE entices
            HER with words about her beauty (for a comparison of HER with a sprout see KT 61).
            T.V.G. has another alternative in taking <term xml:lang="ta">muṟi</term> to mean the
            young leaves of which skirts are made, and than the <term xml:lang="ta">ottaṉa</term>
            ought to mean something like "to be suitable for" (see 4+5b).</note> false[ly
            flattering] things such as</l>
          <l rend="indent4">“these are resembling you”</l>
          <l>and he took me: <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">nalam eṉṉai</term> is a construction problem; it probably has to
            be taken as an apposition: "he took me, [that is, my] virginity".</note>  the choice
            innocence</l>
          <l>protected by mother. Such we [are] now.</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="4+5b">
            <l>He gave [me] a Taḻal and a Taṭṭai and tender leaves [for a garment]</l>
            <l>and talked false[ly flattering] things like “these are suited to you”</l>
          </lg>
          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="4-7c">
              <l>My lord took</l>
              <l>the choice innocence protected by mother,</l>
              <l>giving [me] a Taḻal and a Taṭṭai and a shoot</l>
              <l>[and] talking erroneously “these are apt for you”.</l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
